@jeyhunkarimov could you follow the steps to contribute to a specific JIRA in Kafka?

https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/Contributing+Code+Changes#ContributingCodeChanges-PullRequest

And regarding to your fix, what the JIRA is targeted at is to avoid passing null to the deserializer, since null means the key does not exist in the key-value store. For example, in line 242 of `RocksDBStore` class, when `getInternal(serdes.rawKey(key))` returns null, then we could skip calling `serdes.valueFrom()` on it, which will try to deserialize the returned value but directly return null to the get call.

@guozhangwang 
- Changed my position a bit on the `writeAsText`, files looked better (to me at least) without the label.
- KTables use the name provided at instantiation for the name on the console.

@guozhangwang - addressed all of your comments and made some changes for concurrent access. Things I really need another pair of eyes on
`RocksDBWindowStore`, `RocksDBStore`, `MemoryLRUCache`
Thanks

@guozhangwang about NoOpKeyValueMapper for groupBy I am favourable as it leads to simpler and more concise example. Not sure if the reduce can be simplified further. See for instance:
        KTableImpl<String, String, String> table1 =
            (KTableImpl<String, String, String>) builder.table(stringSerde, stringSerde, topic1);
        KTableImpl<String, String, String> table2 = (KTableImpl<String, String, String>) table1.filter(
            new Predicate<String, String>() {
                @Override
                public boolean test(String key, String value) {
                    return value.equalsIgnoreCase("accept");
                }
            }).groupBy(MockKeyValueMapper.<String, String>NoOpKeyValueMapper())
            .reduce(MockReducer.STRING_ADDER, MockReducer.STRING_REMOVER, "mock-result");

